    <body>
      <pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-JMP007_01.jpg"/>
      <p>
        <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >Children</term>
      </p>
      <p><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >Children</term> arrived in <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >Theresienstadt</placeName> right with the first <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-268" type="subject"
          >transports</term> from <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/3078610/brno.html"
          >Brno</placeName> and <placeName
          ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html"
          >Prague</placeName> in <date when="1941">1941</date>. Thanks to <persName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/terezin-victims-person-iti-1753649"
          type="victim">Gonda Redlich</persName> and <persName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/terezin-victims-person-iti-1459810"
          type="victim">Fredy Hirsch</persName>, who, faithful to the tradition of the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">youth</term>
        movement that they were part of when they were young, immediately brought these <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> under their wing and procured better conditions for them in this worst of
        places, the first special rooms for <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> were soon created and, later, in <date when="1942-02">February
          1942</date>, the first <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190" type="subject"
          >Home for Children</term>. Several people from the <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >ghetto</placeName> administration understood the responsibility we had towards the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> and we tried to find all kinds of ways to make their life in the
          <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >ghetto</placeName> easier. It was once again our <persName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/terezin-victims-person-iti-1296855"
          type="victim">Jakub Edelstein</persName> who, in the difficult and important discussion at
          the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-512">Council of
          Elders</orgName> over whose <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">slice of
          bread</term> would be shortened or whose portion increased, swayed the decision in favor
        of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> with his courageous and lucid analysis. This perhaps unusually and
        cruelly disadvantaged the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-274" type="subject"
          >old</term>, but at the time it was the right thing to do; it guaranteed a better future
        for the Jewish nation. This decision by the <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-512">Council of Elders</orgName>
        trickled down to all of the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject"
          >barracks</term>, kitchens, and streets. Everywhere, <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> came under special care, they were given advantages, and if there was a
        happy sight in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449"
          type="ghetto">Theresienstadt</placeName>, it was surely the happily playing <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term>, who seemed so carefree. But those who worked in <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >Theresienstadt</placeName> with the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> knew how sometimes a <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child’s</term>
        eyes would glisten, knew the look that asked <q>why?</q> to which no <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-48356" type="subject"
          >caretaker</term> knew an appropriate <q>because</q>, knew that when the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> woke up at night they opened their eyes and saw an empty darkness,
        sometimes heard their silent crying that no medicine could cure, knew the complications and
        tragedy of a Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824"
          type="subject">child</term> and its soul. No textbook of psychology exists yet that can
        teach us how to soothe them.</p>
      <p>For the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term>, life in the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190" type="subject"
          >homes</term> was led separately from the rest. In accordance with the principles of
        collective <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-842" type="subject"
          >education</term>, the individual rooms constituted closed <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190" type="subject"
          >homes</term>, which set and managed their daily schedule. Besides their lessons, the
          <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> had to do domestic work and organized frequent evening programs. The
          <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-48356"
          type="subject">caretakers</term><term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">lived</term>
        with the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> and thus they could significantly influence their whole lives.
        Unfortunately, there were very few qualified people, and the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-48356" type="subject"
          >caretaker's</term> incompetence sometimes led to a difficult crisis in the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190" type="subject"
          >home</term>. When the number of <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> in <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >Theresienstadt</placeName> reached its peak, i.e. in the summer of <date when="1943"
          >1943</date>, there were 2,300 <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> aged 4-18 receiving child care in the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190" type="subject"
          >homes</term>. <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-791" type="subject"
          >Health services</term> took care of <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> younger than age 4, placing them either in the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190" type="subject"
          >home</term> for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824"
          type="subject">infants</term> or in the home for <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >toddlers</term> together with their mothers and the staff. <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >Children</term> were not forced to <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">move</term>
        into the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190"
          type="subject">homes</term>. The open <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-8243" type="subject">youth</term>
        care looked after <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824"
          type="subject">children</term> who were outside of the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190" type="subject"
          >homes</term>. The institution of open care consisted of the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190" type="subject"
          >home</term> for mothers and <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> (without a staff), and Czech, German, and Hebrew kindergartens, attended
        by more than 500 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824"
          type="subject">children</term>. Social <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-48344" type="subject"
          >nurses</term> were also part of the open youth care. <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >Children</term> regularly visited them, and the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-48344" type="subject"
          >nurses</term> performed health check-ups and arranged all that was necessary for them,
        within the realm of possibilities. <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >Children</term> up to age 14 who lived with their parents went to the shelters every day,
        where they attended lessons in the most difficult circumstances thanks to the courage and
        devotion of the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-48356" type="subject"
          >caretakers</term> in the face of the <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName>’s strict
        orders against them. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824"
          type="subject">Young people</term> over age 14 who lived either with their parents or in
          <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-190"
          type="subject">homes</term> were <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">forced to
          work</term>. To facilitate this, a special section for the integration of <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">young
          people</term> into the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556"
          type="subject">labor</term> process was created in close cooperation with the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >youth</term> section and <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-jewishcouncil-organisation-jmp-3"
          >labor office</orgName>. In the summer of <date when="1943">1943</date>, a total of 1,673
          <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> were registered in this section. <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">Young
          people</term> were assigned the type of work that would allow them to learn something, for
        example in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-14386"
          type="subject">agriculture</term> and gardening, crafts and production, <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-791" type="subject"
          >healthcare</term> and <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-189" type="subject"
          >education</term>. These <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">young
          people</term>
        
        <pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-JMP007_02.jpg"/>
        
        were also taken care of by a special apprenticeship commission that also
        administered exams once their training was completed. To help with all of these educational
        activities, a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824"
          type="subject">children’s</term>
        <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-jewishcouncil-organisation-jmp-70"
          >library</orgName> for <term type="subject"
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824">children</term> up to age 13
        and a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >young people's</term>
        <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-jewishcouncil-organisation-jmp-70"
          >library</orgName> for older <term type="subject"
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824">children</term> were
        established. Besides the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-842"
          type="subject">caretakers</term>’ ethical and practical goals, the <orgName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-jewishcouncil-organisation-jmp-9"
          >youth section</orgName> tried to expand the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term>’s minds and thus stop the deepening moral decline in the <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >ghetto</placeName>. By pointing to the Jewish nation’s illustrious past and the life and
        work of the future, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-842"
          type="subject">caretakers</term> tried to neutralize the dismalness and hopelessness of
        their situation.</p>
      
      <p>Unfortunately, these efforts were in vain. <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject"
          >Transports</term> continued to arrive and depart; orders and bullying gave the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> no peace. Around 15,000 <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> passed through <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >Theresienstadt</placeName>. A <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-267" type="subject"
          >transport to the east</term> meant a <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term>
        sentence. In the beginning, it was possible to protect <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> younger than 12. But this age limit was gradually lowered, and in <date
          when="1944-10">October 1944</date> even <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">babies</term>
        were transported.</p>
      <p>In the winter of <date when="1944">1944</date>-<date when="1945">1945</date>, 1,068 <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> remained in <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >Theresienstadt</placeName>, and after the war no more than 100 <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> older than 14 returned from the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">concentration
          camps</term>. Unless they were among the fortunate who remained in <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >Theresienstadt</placeName>, no <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term> younger than 14 returned.</p>
      <p>All of the efforts and work, all of the mental and physical care, all of the individual and
        collective <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-842" type="subject"
          >education</term> led nowhere. They could only make the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
          >children</term>’s stay in the <placeName
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto"
          >ghetto</placeName> a little easier.</p>
      
      <p><hi rend="letter-spacing: +2px">They</hi>
        <hi rend="letter-spacing: +2px">couldn’t</hi>
        <hi rend="letter-spacing: +2px">avert</hi>
        <hi rend="letter-spacing: +2px">their</hi>
        <hi rend="letter-spacing: +2px">terrible</hi> <hi rend="letter-spacing: +2px">fate</hi>.</p>
      
      <p><persName ref="#ehri_et_shek_zeev">Zeev Scheck</persName>.</p>
      
      <p>Accepted on behalf of the <term
          ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-657" type="subject"
        >Documentary campaign</term> by: <persName ref="#ehri_et_weinberger_robert">Weinberger</persName></p>
      
      <p>Accepted on behalf of the archive: <persName ref="#ehri_et_tressler_harald">Tressler</persName></p>
      
